This gold ring from the 7th century features lapus lazuli surrounded by pearls. Multicolored jewelry pieces, like this one, were enormously popular in the Byzantine world. See this ring and other stunning objects in our special exhibition Ornament: Fragments of Byzantine Fashion, opening September 10th! Get more details at the link to the exhibition page in our bio.

node.text:
“There is no overarching visage or reigning style that distinguishes the work that is connected with WD. This is both a creative environment and a conceptual space that welcomes abstraction and representational art. Prints are produced here whose ideational framework is largely narrative, as well as principally material and formalist; there are no recognizable camps or clubs that exclude artists who do not speak an official language, or adhere to the latest dress codes.” – Richard J. Powell, excerpt from exhibition catalogue.
.
Victoria Saenz Vogl, “George,” 1998. Etching, 6 x 5 in. Courtesy of the Artist.
.
.

Congratulations to the @NationalParkService on your 103rd birthday. Tudor Place has enjoyed a mutually beneficial relationship with the National Park Service for over five decades. As one of the nation’s first National Historic Landmarks (1960) AND the first historic site with an easement administered by the NPS (1966), Tudor Place is pleased to have been a partner and looks forward to many more years of cooperation. 
Signing the easement agreement with the National Park Service on December 8, 1966. From left, attorney Richard Wilmer, Armistead Peter 3rd (owner of Tudor Place), and Secretary of the Interior Stuart Udall.

🖼 DC is known for its world-class museums on the National Mall, but there are a host of lesser-known museums with unique and exceptional collections and experiences. Locals love the National Bonsai & Penjing Museum @nbfbonsai for its array of manicured trees in a serene setting. 🌳 We also love the modern-art @phillipscollection, just a few minutes from our hotel. Check out our stories for a glimpse at some of DC’s unique museums that you might want to add to your itinerary. After your day of exploring, stop by our living room for One Voice, an art exhibit supporting the LGBTQ community. 📷@atreestate.
.

node.text:
In WASHINGTON DC for few days - Dumbarton Oaks MUSEUM – Middle Byzantine – 10th-11th century – Rosette Coffer with Warriors, Dionysiac Figures and Animals – Bone on wood.
Fait de bois et revêtu de plaques d'os, le coffre est finement recouvert d'un curieux mélange de figures quasi-classiques, y compris des soldats, des érotismes ou des cupides ailés et des animaux.  Le coffre est verrouillable et était donc destiné à protéger les objets de valeur tels que les épices, les parfums ou les pièces de monnaie.
L'influence de l'art byzantin fut sensible en Europe occidentale dès le règne de Charlemagne, qui entretenait des relations étroites avec Byzance. Elle s'est ensuite manifestée, notamment en Italie, dans l'architecture religieuse, lors du développement du style roman aux X et XI siècles. La contribution des intellectuels byzantins émigrés lors de la chute de Constantinople fut également très importante à la Renaissance.
-
Made of wood and clad with bone plaques, the coffer is intricately covered with a curious medley of quasi-classicizing figures, including soldiers, erotes or winged cupids and animals.  The coffer is lockable and therefore was intended to safeguard valuables such as spices, perfumes or coins.
The influence of Byzantine art was noticeable in Western Europe since the reign of Charlemagne, who had close relations with Byzantium. It then manifested itself, especially in Italy, in religious architecture, during the development of the Romanesque style in the 10th and 11th centuries. The contribution of Byzantine intellectuals who emigrated during the fall of Constantinople was also very important in the Renaissance.
-
DUMBARTON OAKS is a historic estate in the Georgetown neighborhood of Washington, D.C. It was the residence and garden of Robert Woods Bliss and his wife Mildred Barnes Bliss. The Dumbarton Oaks Research Library and Collection was founded here by the Bliss couple, who gave the property to Harvard University in 1940.
-

node.text:
Details, details, details…

I don’t often get overwhelmed by a room of art. Especially when I have seen most of the pieces before. Maybe it was the relief of emerging from the somber “Warmth of Other Suns,” Maybe it is just the juxtaposition of 350+ years of western art. Maybe it is the mix of religious themes, with everyday life, and even abstract art. Whatever it is…the main gallery at The Phillips Collection is currently a joy, and delight.It is so packed with goodness that I didn’t even take a photo of the Goya. 
It works together too. El Greco’s work still feels fresh, and vibrant today. His St. Peter is both in conversation with (color scheme), and contrasting to Goya’s St. Peter. Three vertical paintings, by Morris Louis are a pure jolt of color. The fields of van Gogh, and Bacon are a study in scale. Their brushwork carries over to ‘The Luncheon of the Boating Party.’ Renoir’s red and white awning connects with Frankenthaler’s, ‘Canyon.’ The room is not optimal for gaining a perspective on art history. ‘The Boating Party,’ still looks best on its own wall…but every now and then a room like this, simply leaves you breathless.

Opening September 3rd, “Prints & Artists: WD Printmaking Workshop 1970-Present” traces the evolution of the DC-based WD Printmaking workshop founded by Percy and Alice Martin. The pair opened up their Adams Morgan home as a twenty-four hour studio where local artists could come together and experiment with printmaking. The workshop ultimately grew to host classes, present demonstrations, and hold regularly scheduled critique lessons. This exhibition highlights historical and recent works by the members of this workshop.
.
Mark your calendars for our Early Fall Opening Reception, September 7th from 6-9PM! Free and open to all, no RSVP required. See you there!
.
Percy Martin, Untitled, n.d. Etching, paper: 22 1/8 x 29 7/8 in. WD Printmaking Historic Collection.
.

Standing human subjects like the one in this #Egyptian #textile are relatively rare, making this fragment a bit of a mystery. The novelty of the figure's pose, with its raised arms, suggests that this image may originally have represented a different figural form. We'd like to think that he's excited for our new exhibition, Ornament: Fragments of Byzantine Fashion, opening September 10th! Learn more about the exhibition at the link in our bio.

BZ.1953.2.14, Egypt, 7th-10th c., Tapestry Weave in Wool

The Phillips Collection, opened to the public in 1921 in Washington’s vibrant Dupont Circle neighborhood. Paintings by Renoir and Rothko, Bonnard and O'Keeffe, van Gogh and Diebenkorn are among the many stunning impressionist and modern works that fill the museum. Its distinctive building combines extensive new galleries with the former home of its founder, Duncan Phillips.

node.text: From the Glenstone Museum yesterday - omg this place. Every single detail of this sprawling modern art wonder is impeccably designed and unbelievably breathtaking, and I didn’t even see half of it (yet). There were no pictures allowed if the art in the gallery, and for good reason. You have to see it for yourself in conjunction with the building and the other pieces in order to get the real impact. It almost doesn’t even make sense that this place exists and is open to the public, but I’m so grateful that it is and I can experience it. I’m going back the first chance I get! Huge thanks to @shanegerson @samara16 & @blackeyed_susie for sharing this with me!! #glenstonemuseum #dcarts #dcmuseums
